                      <br>
                      <b>European Association for Bioindustries<br>
                      </b>Did you know...<br>
                      - The use of biotechnology has already reduced the
                      carbon footprint of farming where it has been
                      adopted, saving an estimated 14.4 billion kg of
                      CO2 in 2008 - equivalent to the removal of over 6
                      million cars from the roads.[1]<br>
                      <br>
                      - Biotechnology can increase yields by between
                      6-30% on the same amount of land. This means that
                      we can produce more food without having to plough
                      up land that is currently a haven for biodiversity
                      and used for conservation.<br>
                      <br>
                      - There are already 14 million farmers around the
                      world growing GM crops and over 90% are small and
                      resource-poor farmers - more than the total number
                      of farmers in the whole of the EU.<br>
                      <br>
                      - Universities, institutes and companies are field
                      testing crops that require less water (yielding up
                      to 20% more than their non-GM counterparts) and
                      fewer fertilisers, and which are therefore better
                      adapted to the ever-increasing impacts of climate
                      change. <br>
                      <br>
                      &gt; 6 Questions on the Basics of Biotech<br>
                      See: <a
href="http://www.europabio.org/positions/GBE/PP_0906XX_GBE_Manifesto_2009.PDF"
                        target="_blank">http://www.europabio.org/positions/GBE/<br>
                        PP_0906XX_GBE_Manifesto_2009.PDF</a><br>
                      <br>
                      &gt; Water-wise solutions from Agricultural
                      Biotechnology<br>
                      See: <a
                        href="http://www.europabio.org/positions/GBE/PP_101209_water.pdf"
                        target="_blank">http://www.europabio.org/positions/GBE/PP_101209_water.pdf</a><br>
                      <br>
                      &gt; What do European Consumers Really Think about
                      GM Foods?<br>
                      See: <a
                        href="http://www.europabio.org/positions/GBE/PP_101209_consumer.pdf"
                        target="_blank">http://www.europabio.org/positions/GBE/PP_101209_consumer.pdf</a><br>
                      <br>
                      &gt; Coexistence of GM and non-GM crops in the EU:
                      a proven and recognised reality<br>
                      See: <a
                        href="http://www.europabio.org/positions/GBE/PP_100129_coexistence.pdf"
                        target="_blank">http://www.europabio.org/positions/GBE/PP_100129_coexistence.pdf</a><br>
                      <br>
                      &gt; EU Farmers and GM crops: A Matter of Choice<br>
                      See: <a
href="http://www.europabio.org/positions/GBE/PP_100129_Farmerschoice.pdf"
                        target="_blank">http://www.europabio.org/positions/GBE/PP_100129_Farmerschoice.pdf</a><br>
                      <br>
                      Green Biotechnology Manifesto 2009<br>
                      See: <a
